{"parse":{"title":"Baharestan (book)","pageid":51665191,"revid":849201607,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Baharestan</b>, (in Persian: \u0628\u0647\u0627\u0631\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646), (pronounced as <i>B\u01ceh\u0101rest\u0101n</i> or <i>Bahaarestaan</i>) (meaning <i>the land of spring</i>, <i>the spring orchard</i> or <i>the spring garden</i>), is a <a href=\"/wiki/Persian_language\" title=\"Persian language\">Persian</a> book written by <a href=\"/wiki/Jami\" title=\"Jami\">Jami</a> that contains <a href=\"/wiki/Prose\" title=\"Prose\">prose</a>. It has stories, <a href=\"/wiki/Narrative\" title=\"Narrative\">tales</a> and moral advice mainly in prose, but also in <a href=\"/wiki/Poetry\" title=\"Poetry\">poetry</a>. Baharestan is divided into eight <a href=\"/wiki/Chapter_(books)\" title=\"Chapter (books)\">chapters</a>, an introduction, and a final part. Each of its chapters is called a <i>rowzeh</i> (from <a href=\"/wiki/Arabic\" title=\"Arabic\">Arabic</a> rawzah, meaning <i>paradise</i> or <i>heaven</i>). Jami wrote this book in a year in the 9th century after <a href=\"/wiki/Hegira\" title=\"Hegira\">Muhammad's departure</a> to Medina. In the introduction of Baharestan, Jami stated that he had written this book in the style of <a href=\"/wiki/Saadi_Shirazi\" title=\"Saadi Shirazi\">Saadi Shirazi</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/Gulistan_(book)\" title=\"Gulistan (book)\">Gulistan</a> for his son who was ten years old at the time and was studying. Baharestan has content about <a href=\"/wiki/Sufism\" title=\"Sufism\">Sufism</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Mysticism\" title=\"Mysticism\">mysticism</a>. There are 469 <a href=\"/wiki/Verse_(poetry)\" title=\"Verse (poetry)\">verses</a> of poetry in this book; 16 verses being in Arabic and the rest in Persian. Baharestan has <a href=\"/wiki/Saj%27\" title=\"Saj&#39;\">saj'</a> in its texts and the type of its prose is <a href=\"/wiki/Rhymed_prose\" title=\"Rhymed prose\">rhymed prose</a>; i.e. it is rhythmic. Each chapter in Baharestan has a specific topic; for example, in the seventh chapter, the topic is the life and the biography of some poets.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Baharestan_(book)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Persian Wikipedia Contributors. <a class=\"external text\" href=\"https://fa.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%D8%A8%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%A7%D9%86_(%DA%A9%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8)&amp;oldid=18124770\">\u0628\u0647\u0627\u0631\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 (\u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628)</a>. <b>Persian</b>. 19 September 2016; 15:47 (UTC). Translated to English from Persian by the creator of the page.</li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0674067592\">The World of Persian Literary Humanism</a>.</li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation web\"> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://humsci.iaurasht.ac.ir/Files/ThesisProfiles/en/481.pdf\">http://humsci.iaurasht.ac.ir/Files/ThesisProfiles/en/481.pdf</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fhumsci.iaurasht.ac.ir%2FFiles%2FThesisProfiles%2Fen%2F481.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABaharestan+%28book%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> <span style=\"font-size:100%\" class=\"error citation-comment\">Missing or empty <code style=\"color:inherit; border:inherit; padding:inherit;\">&#124;title=</code> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:CS1_errors#citation_missing_title\" title=\"Help:CS1 errors\">help</a>)</span>. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/save/_embed/http://humsci